<section id="research">
  <p class="section-label fade-in">Research</p>
  <h2 class="section-title fade-in">Advancing materials science.</h2>
  <div class="research-card fade-in">
    <p class="rc-label">Composites &middot; NASA Space Grant &middot; Dr. Kedar Kirane</p>
    <h3>Compressive Failure of Woven FRP Composites Under Open Hole Compression</h3>
    <p>Investigating how hole size affects compressive strength in woven fiber-reinforced polymer laminates used in aerospace, automotive, and naval applications. ASTM D6484 OHC tests on hole sizes 3&ndash;6 mm reveal fracture process zone (FPZ) effects that plateau strength beyond ~6 mm. Specimens were cut to half the standard D6484 length to maximize yield from available panel material, and holes were drilled rather than waterjet cut to ensure circular geometry. Sub-scale specimens showed grip-region failure with first-damage gross stress collapsing to 42&ndash;46 MPa regardless of width, suggesting a load-introduction-limited failure mode requiring further investigation.</p>
    <div class="tags" style="margin-bottom:0;"><span class="tag">ASTM D6484</span><span class="tag">OHC Testing</span><span class="tag">FRP Laminates</span><span class="tag">Shimadzu UTM</span><span class="tag">Optical Micrography</span><span class="tag">FPZ Analysis</span></div>
